

 **************  /usr/ipsc/examples/nx_rmf/pi/README  *****************


This directory contains the FORTRAN source and make files for the pi example.
This example computes an approximation of pi by calculating the area
under the curve using the n-point quadrature rule.  The host program
sets up the specific problem, then it collects and reports the results.
Each node performs its part of the calculation independently of the other
nodes and reports back to the host via message passing.  Each node sends 
the total area of its rectangles to the host using a special command, GOP,
which resides in the library "/usr/ipsc/protocode/commutl/rmfort/commlib.a".
This command sums the quantities in these messages so that the host sees
a total rather than individual messages from each node.

The prerequisites for running the example are that you be the "owner" of 
the cube, load the node operating system on it, and have the "commutl"
protocode software installed on your system.  Copy the example directory
to your own user directory if you want to make or change any of these files.
In other words, you should first execute commands like these three:
	1) cp /usr/ipsc/examples/nx_rmf/pi/* <user directory>
	2) getcube
	3) load -c

The makefile is included to create the example programs from source.
Type "make" from within your directory to create the executable programs
(host and node).
  
To actually execute the example you should load the node process onto the
nodes and then execute the host process.  To do this type:

	load node
	host

The host program will ask for 'n', the number of rectangles to use in
approximating pi.  Enter zero or a negative value to exit the program.
